column45:
{color:#333333}*Epic requirement:*{color}

* [{color:#333333}ER.21{color}|https://baplc.sharepoint.com/:x:/r/sites/BAHProjects/(3844b)%20%20Cache%20%20Next%20Gen2/Requirements%20Analysis%20and%20Design/20180215%203844b%20Cache%20Next%20Gen%20PRL%20%20v1.2%20(SF).xlsx?d=w0d3c2f04eae34601817bb33295c20dc9&csf=1&e=VCErDS]

{color:#333333} {color}

{color:#333333}*Background:*{color}

{color:#333333}Commercial currently query the APC by using a variety of SQL queries (scheduled and ad-hoc). {color}

{color:#333333}Scheduled queries (eg Competitor analysis queries) run on an Microsoft SQL Server ( 'bahsql1'). This server is connected directly to the APC Oracle DB as a linked remote server. The Commercial Analysis team maintain both the SQL queries themselves and also the scheduling mechanism on the bahsql1 server. The output of the scheduled queries is returned to the server and stored in the DB. {color}

As well as scheduled queries, ad-hoc queries are also run by the Commercial Analysis team and certain members of Yield. This may be done either on the SQL server (using Teradata) or from users PC's (using SQL Developer). 

A price comparison report (different to Competitor analysis) is one of the more regular ad-hoc reports run by the business.  

The CNG design means that the cached pricing will now be stored in Elasticsearch rather than an Oracle DB and a new mechanism is required for extracting data from the cache. There is also now a separation between the results stored in Elasticsearch and the search records stored in the CMT DB.

The Competitor Analysis team will need the relevant skills for managing the schedule and writing queries. Training may be required for this.



*Requirement:*

{color:#333333}*I want*{color}{color:#333333} to retrieve cached prices by querying the CNG indices {color}{color:#333333}*so that*{color}{color:#333333} BAH prices are able to be:{color}

* {color:#333333}compared with competitors{color}
* used for other commercial analysis tasks as and when required

{color:#333333} {color}

{color:#333333}*Acceptance criteria (high level):*{color}

*AC1 -  Ability to run commercial queries against cached data in Elasticsearch*

{color:#ff5630}*Given*{color} a member Commercial Analysis or Yield has a query that they want to run in Elasticsearch

{color:#ff5630}*When*{color} they submit the query (either as a scheduled job or an ad-hoc query)

{color:#ff5630}*Then*{color} : The query runs and returns data as expected  
  
*Key Info:*

* Currently CA team and Yield use SQL to query the cache and all of the users are trained and have experience in SQL
* Yield team are the business owners of the queries, but they are actually coded by the Commercial Analysis team based on what Yield require
* {color:#333333}Existing SQL queries are attached{color}
* The performance of the current SQL queries is relatively slow (lots of DB joins) and seen as a constraint to the schedule. Ideally CA team would make changes to the schedule such as running queries more frequently or combining regions in queries but current performance prevents this
* {color:#333333}Competitor Analysis have a direct connection between the APC and their BAH SQL database{color}
* Competitor Analysis team will need to be trained in any new technology being implemented
* {color:#333333}Infare are wanting to consume data for Competitor Analysis from CNG via an API. BAH have advised to wait until CNG full API has been implemented and this is not a concern for this JIRA.{color}
* Current performance of the APC queries is seen as a constraint and ideally Commercial would have the capability to run them more frequently if reqd
*  Adhoc query activity is likely to increase around sale activity and peak travel periods
* Commercial Analysis team are intending to move to a Cloud version of Teradata sometime this year - check latest timescales. (And then maybe Snowflake in a few years time)

{color:#333333} {color}

{color:#333333}*Key Stakeholder/s:*{color}

* {color:#333333}Martin Brine{color}
* {color:#333333}Sarah Boyett{color}
* Scott Nimmo
* {color:#333333}Karan Case{color}

{color:#333333} {color}

{color:#333333} {color}{color:#333333}*Design considerations:*{color}

* For scheduled searches we need to confirm whether we have an Elasticsearch solution pushing data to SQL server, or SQL server pulling the data
* The Commercial preference is for the schedule to be controlled on the SQL server but it’s needs to be validated if this is possible
* We also need to determine what query language will be used. The business preference is Elasticsearch’s implementation of SQL rather than DSL (the main JSON style query language). 
* For scheduled searches the business requirement is that the results sets should be automatically sent to the SQL server.
* There should be performance testing of the design solution to confirm that it can handle the expected volumes and frequency of searching
* The design solution should be appropriate for the the skills of the users ie technically aware business users rather than developers.
* CA team are not currently running CO queries, but want the capability of querying that index
* If there are any system limitations on size of results set / speed / paging size etc limiting what’s sensible to run within a single query, then the CA team want to know about this.

{color:#333333}_*As is v To be attached - Competitor Analysis Visio (Note the ‘As-is tab’ is still valid, but the ‘To be’ tab is now out of date)_{color}

{color:#333333} {color}

